<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-10-30T20:48:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-10-30T20:48:00-05:00" n="348" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d348">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">815.00/2102: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul in Charge of the Legation in
                                    Honduras</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Lawton</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tegucigalpa</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-10-30T20:00:00-05:48"><hi rend="italic">October 30, 1919, 8
                                        p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received November 1,
                                        10.30 p.m.</hi>]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>General Gutierrez elected President 76,000 votes to 18,000 votes for
                                Membreño. No serious difficulties occurred during the election.
                                Conditions are quiet. Membreño arrived at Amapala today. I have
                                given my opinion to President Bogran that Membreno cannot now demand
                                the Presidency as Vice President and that Bogran must remain in the
                                chair until formally delivered to President elect. I would like
                                instructions on this subject.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Lawton</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>